The basic pyridine unit has a melting point around 20°C, but a number of substituents alter this significantly. Amino groups generally raise the melting point because of strong intermolecular hydrogen bonding: each amino group can add roughly +80°C. The amide group also raises the melting point due to hydrogen bonding and increased resonance stability; we can estimate +50°C for that. The presence of a fluorobenzyl group adds aromaticity and increased molecular rigidity, which tends to raise the melting point as well; this might contribute about +40°C. Lastly, the ethoxy carbamate group is relatively large and may introduce further rigidity and dispersion forces, which could add about +20°C. Therefore, the final estimated melting point can be calculated as follows: 20 (pyridine) + 80 (amino) + 80 (secondary amino) + 50 (amide) + 40 (fluorobenzyl) + 20 (ethoxy carbamate) = 290°C.
